Note:
Platform Interface - Cross-Platform Syscall Abstraction Layer

Defines the platform-agnostic types and constants that all platform-specific syscall
modules implement. Each platform (Linux x86_64, Darwin ARM64, Windows x86_64, etc.)
provides its own syscall number mappings and calling conventions, but they all
conform to the types defined here.

This file provides:
- SyscallDefinition: metadata for a single syscall (number, name, arg count, arg types)
- PlatformInfo: metadata about a target platform (arch, OS, pointer size, endianness)
- SyscallConvention: register assignments for syscall invocation per platform
- SyscallArgType: argument type classifications for type-safe syscall emission

Dependencies:
- Imports memory layout for type allocation
- Imports list/dictionary for collection management
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Platform ID Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64 as Integer is 1
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM64 as Integer is 2
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM32 as Integer is 3
Constant PLATFORM_DARWIN_X86_64 as Integer is 4
Constant PLATFORM_DARWIN_ARM64 as Integer is 5
Constant PLATFORM_WINDOWS_X86_64 as Integer is 6
Constant PLATFORM_WINDOWS_ARM64 as Integer is 7
Constant PLATFORM_FREEBSD_X86_64 as Integer is 8
Constant PLATFORM_FREEBSD_ARM64 as Integer is 9
Constant PLATFORM_OPENBSD_X86_64 as Integer is 10
Constant PLATFORM_OPENBSD_ARM64 as Integer is 11
Constant PLATFORM_NETBSD_X86_64 as Integer is 12
Constant PLATFORM_NETBSD_ARM64 as Integer is 13
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32 as Integer is 14
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64 as Integer is 15
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC as Integer is 16
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV32 as Integer is 17
Constant PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV64 as Integer is 18
Constant PLATFORM_WASM_WASI as Integer is 19

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Endianness Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant ENDIAN_LITTLE as Integer is 0
Constant ENDIAN_BIG as Integer is 1

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Syscall Argument Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Syscall argument types classify the kind of data each syscall argument expects.
This enables the compiler to emit appropriate register sizing, sign extension,
and validation at compile time. For example, a pointer argument on x86_64 must
be in a 64-bit register, while a flags argument may be 32-bit.
@End Reasoning

Constant SYSCALL_ARG_INT as Integer is 1            Note: Integer value (signed or unsigned)
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_UINT as Integer is 2           Note: Unsigned integer
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_PTR as Integer is 3            Note: Pointer to memory
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_SIZE as Integer is 4           Note: Size/length value
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_FLAGS as Integer is 5          Note: Bitfield flags
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_FD as Integer is 6             Note: File descriptor
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_MODE as Integer is 7           Note: File mode/permissions
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_OFFSET as Integer is 8         Note: File offset (may be 64-bit)
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_PID as Integer is 9            Note: Process ID
Constant SYSCALL_ARG_SIGNAL as Integer is 10        Note: Signal number

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Syscall Category Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant SYSCALL_CAT_FILE_IO as Integer is 1        Note: File I/O operations
Constant SYSCALL_CAT_MEMORY as Integer is 2         Note: Memory management operations
Constant SYSCALL_CAT_PROCESS as Integer is 3        Note: Process management
Constant SYSCALL_CAT_NETWORK as Integer is 4        Note: Network operations
Constant SYSCALL_CAT_TIME as Integer is 5           Note: Time/clock operations
Constant SYSCALL_CAT_SIGNAL as Integer is 6         Note: Signal handling

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SyscallDefinition Type
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
SyscallDefinition encapsulates everything known about a single system call:
its platform-specific number, canonical name, argument count, argument type
classifications, return type, and category. This metadata enables:
1. Code generation to emit the correct syscall number and register setup
2. Compile-time validation of syscall argument counts and types
3. Cross-platform abstraction (same name maps to different numbers per platform)
4. Security auditing (categorization enables permission checking)
@End Reasoning

Type called "SyscallDefinition":
    syscall_number as Integer         Note: Platform-specific syscall number
    syscall_name as Integer           Note: Pointer to canonical name string (e.g., "read")
    arg_count as Integer              Note: Number of arguments (0-6)
    arg_types as Integer              Note: Pointer to list of SYSCALL_ARG_* constants
    return_type as Integer            Note: SYSCALL_ARG_* constant for return type
    category as Integer               Note: SYSCALL_CAT_* category constant
    platform_id as Integer            Note: PLATFORM_* constant this definition belongs to
    is_noreturn as Integer            Note: 1 if syscall never returns (e.g., exit)
End Type

Note: Size: 8 fields * 8 bytes = 64 bytes per SyscallDefinition

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PlatformInfo Type
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
PlatformInfo describes a target platform's characteristics that affect syscall
emission and general code generation. This includes the architecture, OS,
pointer size (which affects argument register sizing), endianness (which affects
data layout in syscall buffers), and the syscall instruction mechanism.

The syscall_instruction field points to the assembly instruction string used to
invoke syscalls on this platform (e.g., "syscall" for x86_64, "svc #0" for ARM64).
@End Reasoning

Type called "PlatformInfo":
    platform_id as Integer            Note: PLATFORM_* constant
    arch as Integer                   Note: TARGET_ARCH_* constant from machine_code_interface
    os as Integer                     Note: TARGET_OS_* constant from machine_code_interface
    pointer_size as Integer           Note: Pointer size in bytes (4 or 8)
    endianness as Integer             Note: ENDIAN_LITTLE or ENDIAN_BIG
    syscall_instruction as Integer    Note: Pointer to syscall instruction string
    syscall_number_register as Integer Note: Register ID for syscall number
    max_syscall_args as Integer       Note: Maximum syscall arguments supported (usually 6)
    platform_name as Integer          Note: Pointer to human-readable platform name
    abi_name as Integer               Note: Pointer to ABI name string (e.g., "System V")
End Type

Note: Size: 10 fields * 8 bytes = 80 bytes per PlatformInfo

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SyscallConvention Type
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
SyscallConvention specifies the register assignments for syscall invocation on a
given platform. Each platform uses different registers to pass the syscall number
and arguments. For example:
- Linux x86_64: RAX=number, RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9=args
- Linux ARM64: X8=number, X0-X5=args
- Darwin x86_64: RAX=number+0x2000000, RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9=args

The error_in_carry flag indicates whether errors are signaled via the carry flag
(as on some BSD platforms) rather than through a negative return value.
@End Reasoning

Type called "SyscallConvention":
    platform_id as Integer            Note: PLATFORM_* constant
    number_register as Integer        Note: Register for syscall number (e.g., RAX on x86_64)
    arg_registers as Integer          Note: Pointer to list of 6 register IDs for args
    return_register as Integer        Note: Register for return value (e.g., RAX on x86_64)
    error_register as Integer         Note: Register for error flag (0 if errors in return)
    clobber_registers as Integer      Note: Pointer to list of registers clobbered by syscall
    syscall_number_offset as Integer  Note: Offset added to syscall number (0x2000000 on Darwin)
    error_in_carry as Integer         Note: 1 if error signaled via carry flag (some BSDs)
End Type

Note: Size: 8 fields * 8 bytes = 64 bytes per SyscallConvention

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SyscallDefinition Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_syscall_definition" that takes number as Integer, name as Integer, arg_count as Integer, category as Integer, platform_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Creates a SyscallDefinition with the given parameters
    Let def be Layout.allocate(64)
    If def is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(def, 0, number)
    __store(def, 8, name)
    __store(def, 16, arg_count)

    Note: Create arg types list (up to 6 args)
    Let arg_types be List.list_create(6)
    __store(def, 24, arg_types)

    Note: Default return type is integer
    __store(def, 32, SYSCALL_ARG_INT)
    __store(def, 40, category)
    __store(def, 48, platform_id)
    __store(def, 56, 0)

    Return def
End Process

Process called "syscall_def_set_arg_type" that takes def as Integer, arg_index as Integer, arg_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Sets the type of a specific argument in the syscall definition
    If def is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arg_index < 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arg_count be __load(def, 16)
    If arg_index >= arg_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arg_types be __load(def, 24)
    If arg_types is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Ensure list is long enough
    Let current_len be List.list_length(arg_types)
    While current_len <= arg_index:
        List.list_append(arg_types, SYSCALL_ARG_INT)
        Set current_len to current_len + 1
    End While

    List.list_set(arg_types, arg_index, arg_type)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "syscall_def_set_noreturn" that takes def as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Marks a syscall as never returning (e.g., exit)
    If def is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(def, 56, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "syscall_def_get_number" that takes def as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the platform-specific syscall number
    If def is 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return __load(def, 0)
End Process

Process called "syscall_def_get_name" that takes def as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the pointer to the syscall name string
    If def is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(def, 8)
End Process

Process called "syscall_def_get_arg_count" that takes def as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the number of arguments the syscall takes
    If def is 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return __load(def, 16)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PlatformInfo Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_platform_info" that takes platform_id as Integer, arch as Integer, os as Integer, pointer_size as Integer, endianness as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Creates a PlatformInfo with the given parameters
    Let info be Layout.allocate(80)
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(info, 0, platform_id)
    __store(info, 8, arch)
    __store(info, 16, os)
    __store(info, 24, pointer_size)
    __store(info, 32, endianness)

    Note: Set syscall instruction based on architecture
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_X86_64:
        __store(info, 40, "syscall")
        __store(info, 48, 0)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_AARCH64:
        __store(info, 40, "svc #0")
        __store(info, 48, 8)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_ARM32:
        __store(info, 40, "swi 0")
        __store(info, 48, 7)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_RISCV64:
        __store(info, 40, "ecall")
        __store(info, 48, 17)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_RISCV32:
        __store(info, 40, "ecall")
        __store(info, 48, 17)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_MIPS64:
        __store(info, 40, "syscall")
        __store(info, 48, 2)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_MIPS32:
        __store(info, 40, "syscall")
        __store(info, 48, 2)
    End If
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_POWERPC:
        __store(info, 40, "sc")
        __store(info, 48, 0)
    End If

    Note: Maximum 6 syscall arguments on most platforms
    __store(info, 56, 6)
    __store(info, 64, 0)
    __store(info, 72, 0)

    Return info
End Process

Process called "platform_info_set_name" that takes info as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Sets the human-readable platform name
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(info, 64, name)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "platform_info_set_abi" that takes info as Integer, abi_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Sets the ABI name string
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(info, 72, abi_name)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "platform_get_pointer_size" that takes info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the pointer size in bytes for this platform
    If info is 0:
        Return 8
    End If
    Return __load(info, 24)
End Process

Process called "platform_is_little_endian" that takes info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if platform is little-endian, 0 if big-endian
    If info is 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let endianness be __load(info, 32)
    If endianness is ENDIAN_LITTLE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SyscallConvention Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_syscall_convention" that takes platform_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Creates a SyscallConvention for the given platform with correct register assignments
    Let conv be Layout.allocate(64)
    If conv is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    __store(conv, 0, platform_id)

    Note: Create argument register list and clobber list
    Let arg_regs be List.list_create(6)
    Let clobbers be List.list_create(8)

    Note: Set register assignments based on platform
    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)       Note: RAX for syscall number
        Note: Args: RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)   Note: RDI
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)   Note: RSI
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)   Note: RDX
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)  Note: R10 (not RCX, which is clobbered by syscall)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)   Note: R8
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)   Note: R9
        __store(conv, 24, 0)      Note: Return in RAX
        __store(conv, 32, 0)      Note: No separate error register
        Note: Clobbered: RCX, R11 (by syscall instruction)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 2)   Note: RCX
        List.list_append(clobbers, 11)  Note: R11
        __store(conv, 48, 0)      Note: No syscall number offset
        __store(conv, 56, 0)      Note: No error-in-carry
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_DARWIN_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)       Note: RAX for syscall number
        Note: Args: RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9 (same as Linux)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 2)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 11)
        __store(conv, 48, 33554432)  Note: 0x2000000 offset for Darwin/macOS
        __store(conv, 56, 1)      Note: Darwin uses carry flag for errors
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_WINDOWS_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)       Note: RAX/EAX for syscall number
        Note: Windows syscalls use RCX, RDX, R8, R9 (like Win64 ABI), then stack
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)  Note: R10 (RCX value moved to R10 before syscall)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)   Note: RDX
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)   Note: R8
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)   Note: R9
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)   Note: Stack arg 1 (placeholder reg ID)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)   Note: Stack arg 2 (placeholder reg ID)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 8)       Note: X8 for syscall number
        Note: Args: X0-X5
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)   Note: X0
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)   Note: X1
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)   Note: X2
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)   Note: X3
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)   Note: X4
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)   Note: X5
        __store(conv, 24, 0)      Note: Return in X0
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_DARWIN_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 16)      Note: X16 for syscall number on Darwin ARM64
        Note: Args: X0-X5
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)      Note: Darwin uses carry flag for errors
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM32:
        __store(conv, 8, 7)       Note: R7 for syscall number
        Note: Args: R0-R5
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV64:
        __store(conv, 8, 17)      Note: a7 (x17) for syscall number
        Note: Args: a0-a5 (x10-x15)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)  Note: a0
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 11)  Note: a1
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 12)  Note: a2
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 13)  Note: a3
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 14)  Note: a4
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 15)  Note: a5
        __store(conv, 24, 10)     Note: Return in a0
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV32:
        __store(conv, 8, 17)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 11)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 12)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 13)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 14)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 15)
        __store(conv, 24, 10)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32:
        __store(conv, 8, 2)       Note: $v0 for syscall number
        Note: Args: $a0-$a3 (4 register args, rest on stack)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)   Note: $a0
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)   Note: $a1
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 6)   Note: $a2
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 7)   Note: $a3
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)   Note: Stack arg
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)   Note: Stack arg
        __store(conv, 24, 2)      Note: Return in $v0
        __store(conv, 32, 7)      Note: Error in $a3
        __store(conv, 48, 4000)   Note: MIPS o32 syscall base offset
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64:
        __store(conv, 8, 2)       Note: $v0 for syscall number
        Note: N64 ABI: $a0-$a5
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 6)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 7)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)
        __store(conv, 24, 2)
        __store(conv, 32, 7)
        __store(conv, 48, 5000)   Note: MIPS n64 syscall base offset
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)       Note: r0 for syscall number
        Note: Args: r3-r8
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 6)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 7)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        __store(conv, 24, 3)      Note: Return in r3
        __store(conv, 32, 0)      Note: Error via CR0.SO bit
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)      Note: Error signaled via condition register
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_FREEBSD_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)       Note: RAX
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 2)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 11)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)      Note: FreeBSD uses carry for errors
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_FREEBSD_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_OPENBSD_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 2)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 11)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_OPENBSD_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_NETBSD_X86_64:
        __store(conv, 8, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 10)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 9)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 2)
        List.list_append(clobbers, 11)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 1)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_NETBSD_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 8)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    If platform_id is PLATFORM_WINDOWS_ARM64:
        __store(conv, 8, 8)       Note: X8 for syscall number on Windows ARM64
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 0)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 1)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 2)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 3)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 4)
        List.list_append(arg_regs, 5)
        __store(conv, 24, 0)
        __store(conv, 32, 0)
        __store(conv, 48, 0)
        __store(conv, 56, 0)
    End If

    __store(conv, 16, arg_regs)
    __store(conv, 40, clobbers)

    Return conv
End Process

Process called "convention_get_arg_register" that takes conv as Integer, arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the register ID for the given syscall argument index
    If conv is 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If arg_index < 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If arg_index >= 6:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let arg_regs be __load(conv, 16)
    If arg_regs is 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Return List.list_get(arg_regs, arg_index)
End Process

Process called "convention_get_number_register" that takes conv as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the register ID used for the syscall number
    If conv is 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return __load(conv, 8)
End Process

Process called "convention_get_return_register" that takes conv as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the register ID where the syscall return value appears
    If conv is 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return __load(conv, 24)
End Process

Process called "convention_get_syscall_offset" that takes conv as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the offset added to syscall numbers (e.g., 0x2000000 for Darwin)
    If conv is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(conv, 48)
End Process

Process called "convention_uses_carry_error" that takes conv as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if errors are signaled via carry flag
    If conv is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return __load(conv, 56)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Platform Detection Utility
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_platform_id" that takes arch as Integer, os as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the PLATFORM_* constant for the given arch+os combination
    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_X86_64:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_DARWIN:
            Return PLATFORM_DARWIN_X86_64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_WINDOWS:
            Return PLATFORM_WINDOWS_X86_64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_FREEBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_FREEBSD_X86_64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_OPENBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_OPENBSD_X86_64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_NETBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_NETBSD_X86_64
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_AARCH64:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_DARWIN:
            Return PLATFORM_DARWIN_ARM64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_WINDOWS:
            Return PLATFORM_WINDOWS_ARM64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_FREEBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_FREEBSD_ARM64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_OPENBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_OPENBSD_ARM64
        End If
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_NETBSD:
            Return PLATFORM_NETBSD_ARM64
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_ARM32:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_ARM32
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_MIPS32:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS32
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_MIPS64:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_MIPS64
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_POWERPC:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_POWERPC
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_RISCV32:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV32
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_RISCV64:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX:
            Return PLATFORM_LINUX_RISCV64
        End If
    End If

    If arch is MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_WASM32:
        If os is MachineCode.TARGET_OS_WASI:
            Return PLATFORM_WASM_WASI
        End If
    End If

    Return -1
End Process
